## **History of Arsenal Enterprise → Arsenal Engines**

**Prior to SS1**

- In our world, throughout history, cyclopes were involved in blacksmithing, talented metalworkers by nature, resistant to the heat and arduous conditions, able to maintain focus on the red-hot molten point of a blade, without the need for depth of field specific to detailed work that humans and dwarves in particular had a knack for.   
  There were genetic complications that led to disease and early death when breeding cyclopes with one another, so their pure-blooded numbers were scarce, and the single eye being recessive meant that hybrids could pass for another ethnicity, and did well to, due to discrimination and being labelled as disease-ridden ‘monsters’. Commonly sick as children, they were often turned away from medical care by the mainstream community.  
  [Silas](https://docs.google.com/document/u/0/d/1f8cGJSwesarhFOSSwii3eBQ3HPg7ktCadf7WFQDOP8k/edit)’s parents, Richard and Divina, however, were a rare success story. Divina was the heir to a wealthy shipping magnate, Perry Billings, who sold his business for an early retirement. Meanwhile, Devina’s mother, Cassandra, set her sights on finding a suitable husband for her daughter. Divina met Richard by her own volition, however, at a dwarf-run tattoo parlour on the East End, where a girl of her station most certainly was not allowed, but where she met Richard as he was finishing up his sleeve, the image of red dragon coiled around a sceptre, forever etched as his fate would soon be etched with Devina’s.  
  At that time, Richard was a sought-after contractor and gang boss in the London shipyards, beating up construction workers who wanted the same contract, and supervising the construction of steam-and-sail powered vessels carrying auspicious cargo. While courting Divina, he cut off his other relationships, even spurning his friends to make time for the woman he knew better than any premonition was the love of his life. Once they had lived for a year together in a modest tenement in Bethnal Green, he proposed to her the same weekend that he put down initial payment on a warehouse space in which the world-famous Arsenal Enterprise would soon enough reside.   
  Over the years, Arsenal expanded beyond private clients, taking on government contracts to design, manufacture, and install highly-specialised cannons and guns for the British armada of battleships, cruisers, luggers, and brigs. **With an arm of operations dedicated to arming the Crown’s conquests, Arsenal then expanded to medical equipment and devices, at first on a lark, but then to their great financial boon, as they accumulated clientele beyond the Church-sponsored hospitals to the private sanitariums and specialised surgery clinics, on the cutting edge of medical advancement.**   
  By the verge of his and his wife’s untimely deaths, Richard had amassed an astonishing fortune, and re-branded Arsenal Enterprise as Arsenal Engines, deciding to focus on the specific technologies that brought his proud nation healing and medical advancement rather than damage and ruin, announcing to the press his decision to move away from weapons manufacturing to the  production of limbs, prosthetics, saws, scalpels, and other medical machinery.  
  He served the interests of his powerhouse nation until the end, when he and Devina died in an explosion that could only have been orchestrated by one of his industro-political rivals, most likely a hate crime against an all too prominent cyclops family. That being said, no one, be it group or individual, ever claimed responsibility. Richard Bragg’s business partners and confidants all agreed it was an outright assassination, although they could not produce a culprit, and after a halfhearted police investigation, the search for evidence became a lost cause.  
  **Silas is the second Lord Bragg \- the hereditary peerage was at first bestowed upon his father, Richard Bragg, for a part he played in discovering Atlantis and bringing its secrets back to England, namely the Atlantians' use of the advanced steam technology.**


**Prior to SS2**

- Seeing the Core installation at the end of SS1 as a failure, he’s turned back to an old project to use more of a biological rather than mechanical solution to correct his spine and allow him to walk again. With Arsenal Engines haemorrhaging money, he’s abandoned his responsibilities there and fired his staff and is now hanging in the warehouse acting like a recluse and working on a project.

## **Silas’s sister’s death** 

- Silas had a sister named Laura. She was a sick child like him, and for cyclopes who breed with other cyclopes, frailty and illness is common—short lifespans—which serves to explain their minority share of population. Although it couldn’t be diagnosed as such, Laura had [multiple sclerosis](https://dodgepark.com/health/debilitating-diseases/), a rare [disorder](https://mstrust.org.uk/a-z/history-ms) that subjected her body and brain to a slow [deterioration](https://mstrust.org.uk/a-z/end-stage-ms#:~:text=It%20is%20rare%2C%20although%20not,which%20can%20lead%20to%20death.). Her physicians said she wouldn’t live past ten years of age. MS weakened her respiratory muscles and created feeding difficulties, making her susceptible to respiratory infections as well as aspiration pneumonia, where food or fluid enters the lungs.  
- She was twelve when her disease at last won the battle. Silas, already an aspiring medical student, which his parents encouraged, felt compelled to commit to learning medicine with the hopes to create a breathing apparatus that would’ve saved Laura, and would save others like her. As it would turn out, he would need synthetic lungs himself, although his designs were only dreams then.  
- Alternatively, Laura might’ve suffered from Polio, Scoliosis, Spina bifida, Muscular Dystrophy (MD), Cerebral Palsy, or Cystic Fibrosis (lung condition)

## **Antonia, dwarven handmaid to the Bragg family**

- An ancillary character who is loyal to the bitter end, and believes in Silas because of their history and because she admires his genius and has put him on a pedestal of scientific grandeur in her own mind. With little other to pursue in her own life, she has latched onto Silas’s pursuits to find meaning. Brain augmentation is too cyberpunk, but Antonia does have one arm replaced with a mechanical one that accepts new programming via punch cards as they are developed.  
- Antonia’s mother was one of many chambermaids on the Bragg estate. As a widow, she was completely dependent on this income and the home provided for her only child. Behind the scenes, the mother encouraged Antonia to play with the wealthy Bragg children, with whom the girl luckily had a natural rapport.  
- Later, Richard Bragg would discover that Antonia had a natural aptitude for any kind of machinery, from detailed clockwork mechanisms to diagrams of heavy industrial equipment. After that, she was included in all of the Bragg children’s education, and eventually apprenticed with Lord Bragg himself while Silas enrolled in medical school.  
- Especially gifted with finely-detailed machinery, Antonia grew up serving the Bragg family, one of Silas and Laura’s few playmates, where the three would spend hours with free reign of Richard’s workshop, even into the evenings, when Richard would set aside the mess they had made, and give them real instruction that in the case of Antonia and Silas, would stick with them for a lifetime of successful mechanical inventions.  
- As Silas became more interested in medical devices and augmentations, Antonia went to medical school to be of even better service, and is now a Consulting Physician and Surgeon at the [Bethnal House Sanitarium](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1p5iMx_0NbmLG_aEsIHoeaS248MCeJky5eWFvLa4J0mE/edit?usp=sharing)


## **The ‘accident’ that killed Silas’s parents**  {#the-‘accident’-that-killed-silas’s-parents}

- As his parents begin to speak freely about the rights of Cyclopes, a carriage bomb explodes at a fundraising event, but young Silas, seventeen, in his first year of medical school, one year after his sister, Marie, had died, was playing chess with the young master of the house, and was allowed by his parents to go back and say goodbye, or is simply dawdling, as the parents walk to the carriage and when the driver opens the door, the latch triggers a load of dynamite, killing both parents and the driver, and blowing back young Silas into one of the Georgian columns in front of the manor where the event was being held. One of his lungs was pierced by a piece of shrapnel, giving him an immediate need to pursue his augmentations. With extra pressure now on his one working lung, he began to hurriedly draw schematics for brass-polymer fibre lungs. He was so obsessive about his work that he didn’t see the point in the busy-work he was assigned in medical school, and what with his recuperation from his injury, he decided to drop out and pursue his medical education on his own, aided by Antonia, with her knack for mechanical engineering.  
  After his sister and then his parents, Silas was plagued by such thoughts as, ‘Am I doomed to repeat the same turns that I see in other’s lives, the same pattern of illness and tragedy that’s befallen my family?’ But after counsel with Antonia, he resolved to escape the cycles, although he never again trusted the free-hand of humanity to run its own course, deciding to use his privilege and wealth to intervene. He began to obsess over protecting and guiding his fellow Britons into a brighter future, be it by copper bones, artificial organs, or a whole host of body augmentations.  
  In his early thirties, Silas began looking to religion as a means to gather more followers, because his vision of a mechanised future required public support. He did not intend to subjugate the population, but rather wanted people to join voluntarily, and he saw religion as a catalyst with which to generate genuine belief in his cause. Not that he’s cynical towards religion, just sees it as a manipulation tool. Then again, religion is hard as a manipulation tool, whereas existing political or nationalist-political structures are easier to get people committed to, so *maybe worth a pivot to that, instead.*   
  **New direction — Silas is not a cult leader, but rather a rich industrialist who genuinely believes in advancing medicine through technology, and lengthening lifespans with plenty of free will decisions still available to the populace.**

## **The Broad, centralised Church legitimises the Caruso sect (BACKSTORY)**

- At Father Franco’s urging, Silas adopted the cause of a little known saint, Saint Caruso, who was slain by the Moors in the 13th century. The story goes that he was a talented healer and carver of prosthetic limbs, but was persecuted for trying to convert his patients. (possibly the truth was that he experimented with more than just prosthetics, creating diagrams, like DaVinci, that couldn’t be implemented until centuries later)  
- Franco convinced the Church to promote this saint—using his name for his hospital—as a conciliatory bribe to secularists, and a counter to the influence of the Broad Church and the threat of Darwinism. "We are not against scientific progress, but since all progress descends from God’s grace, God must take precedence in all things." Saint Caruso is tied to their hospital, which they promote as **a house of miracles rather than Science**.  
- The Catholic splinter group now call themselves the Sons of Saint Caruso, with the Latin motto: From the Blessing of Science, Healing. [Eli the Cyclops preacher](https://docs.google.com/document/u/0/d/1YVufFRSyOWZ0_WtjPrFC6uvYJtQ9ucQZq28kf6boexM/edit), once a close follower and friend of Franco’s was left in the dust by Franco when he teamed up with Silas, who had the money to be his patron, and Eli also realised the dark turn the Cult of Caruso was taking.  
- This means in Leo’s Quest, an important entry gated by a skill check at Eli.

## **Silas’s Earth-shaking Invention**

- Vice-driven and seedy like something used for gambling or to sustain functional drug use— within our theme that people can be controlled by their vices if they aren’t careful. Silas: “*Men are fooled by a false sense of freedom, believing they control their lives when they are in fact commanded by all sorts of desires made by the hand of the market. The people choose which poison they like, until choice becomes an illusion. Because they are already blind, taking control is a simple manipulation of cause and effect. We produce a product that everyone will want, and the people think they’ve chosen to want it, but in fact we’ve chosen it for them. This catalyst is necessary for mankind to reach its potential.*”  
- Preventative Care Implants; once they’re used to being steam-cyborgs, start producing them for poor people; eventually command the whole market  
- In Bioshock — people get addicted to gene splicing but the more you use it, the more you lose your mind  
- This is also the plot of Deus Ex: Human Revolution

## **19th Century Medical Devices**

- Ecraseur: Used in the 19th century, this instrument strangled uterine and ovarian tumours as well as haemorrhoids. Its wire loop or chain was placed around the base of the unwanted growth and gradually tightened. That would eventually either cut through the base of the growth, or cut off its blood supply until it gave up and dropped off. Doing this was painful, particularly with haemorrhoids, but experts of the day argued that the pain was short-lived compared with cutting.

## **The Dockhounds get involved**

- [Molly of the Hounds](https://docs.google.com/document/u/0/d/1g_7OIbd7x3jUoWNqrkn9Ob9LedbfSJgfS1SFaGGdumw/edit) is no trouble for Bragg to recruit, because when Silas was in medical school, Jack O’Malley, Molly’s now-deceased husband who was then leading the Hounds, was already encouraging his recruits to get augmentations, so she wants to keep his legacy alive, to the point that she has such moral blind spots as being willing to harvest organs from orphan,  so by the time she and Silas join forces, she is ready for more extreme experiments.   
- Before long, the Hounds are raising money for the Cult and their own **Augmentation Initiative**, extorting it from local businesses, and skimming off the lucrative underground gambling industry, not only on streets of London and in the gentleman’s clubs, but in the parlours of the Royals and the highest Lords of Parliament, as unregulated vices run rampant throughout London.  
- Over the past ten years, the Dockhounds have raged unchecked across London and muscled their way into every kind of vice. Their scourging of the other criminal gangs has been tacitly welcomed for a number of reasons: less visible (on the street) violence, only one gang for the police to deal with (collect bribes from), one-stop shopping for illicit goods/activities. Also, their reputation for brutality is balanced by a tangible sense of fairness. “Those what pays on time gets no trouble.” They’re businessmen conducting what is sometimes a dirty, difficult business, and they do their best to keep the law-abiding public out of it. Though if the truth were to come out regarding their bottommost unsavoury activities—harvesting organs from orphans—there might be trouble. Orphans are targeted because (sadly) they put up less of a fight, and because homeless people (as adults) are more likely to have damaged their organs with alcohol and drugs, while orphans haven't yet had that chance.  
- The cult is the real authority controlling the Dockhounds, though the thugs themselves may be unaware of it. For the police and political figures, Martina ‘Molly’ O’Malley is the exotic ringleader keeping these goons in check. Money from the Dockhounds’ numerous criminal endeavours goes straight to an off-the-books account which funds Silas’s immoral and illegal human experimentation. Thus, **to the world, Silas is a moneyed philanthropist who pays his taxes, supports many charities, and has no connection to the Dockhounds.**  
- Part of the reason for the Dockhounds’ massive success in the London underworld is the ferocity and nigh inhuman endurance of their strongarms, who are universally equipped with (mostly hidden) augmentations from Arsenal Engines. **A fat and regular (like clockwork) tithe keeps the Church of England uninterested in the details of their labours.** And if the underworld should need to be brought to heel, better if one of their own was in charge.  
- After a few years working with the Hounds and fitting the grunt labour with enhancements, Bragg began to critique the inherent stupidity of man, doubting his initial vision of ‘bringing everyone into a brighter future.’ He starts to see the sacrifice of innocents, in particular the underprivileged, as a necessary evil to achieve his aims, and he thinks that the future he desires was prophesied in the religious texts that he now thinks are the Absolute Truth.  
- A few years after sealing his very profitable alliance with the Dockhounds, Silas realised they made the perfect subjects for his experimental implants—they were typically young, relatively healthy or at least well fed, and would immediately benefit from increased strength and endurance, and resistance to pain. This also makes sense economically, as the Dockhounds provide an almost [instant re](#bookmark=id.h0aiq5e8btma)turn on investment. \*But\* good henchmen aren’t disposable, it’s demoralising to their peers when they die or are crippled, and costly for Molly.   
- (At right) the ‘Antonia arm,’ designed for Silas’s trusted confidant, and used on otherwise crippled Hounds. To keep it steampunk, the workings of the arm are still visible—mostly mechanical with some dried, stretched and preserved animal tendons that need to be rewound and replaced every two weeks, but for Art, we can mostly just show the shiny brass outer-workings  
- This dilemma is combined with bitterness that, as the years pass, Silas cannot create a mechanism that allows him to walk—“Why is locomotion the only thing my genius cannot grant? Does God deny me because I am superior to His creation?”—leading to the realisation that quantity of subjects is as important as quality if he is to swiftly advance his agenda. Naturally, those who will not be missed will make the best subjects, but the homeless and poor have weaker constitutions—thus the orphans, access to which Franco conveniently provides.  
- Regarding religious texts, they could tie in nicely with Saint Caruso and his unsavoury backstory.

#### *Older Notes*

- Crippled in his youth, this Belgian Cyclops (?) inherited a boatload of money, with which he created a mechanical ventilation system to sustain his body/lungs/respiratory system, and to be able to live longer in general. During a sacrificial ceremony, he should wear a Surplice. He isn't evil so much as a victim of his upbringing and circumstance that perverted his world view.

These events were, in part, associated with the wider European Protestant Reformation, a religious and political movement that affected the practice of Christianity in western and central Europe. Causes included the invention of the printing press, increased circulation of the Bible and the transmission of new knowledge and ideas among scholars, the upper and middle classes and readers in general. The phases of the English Reformation, which also covered Wales and Ireland, were largely driven by changes in government policy, to which public opinion gradually accommodated itself.
